      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Infectar</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> To say that there will be no character transfer is to restate the obvious as that point has already been made numerous times in this post up to now.  What the heck though I'm entitled to repeat the obvious if I so desire.  With the radically different basic frameworks the two games have (or will have)there is no way this would have ever been feasible.  </P><P>With regard to pulling the plug on EQ and leaving us all out in the cold, well I must have missed something in that press release.  No where did I read that VI has any plans to shut EQ down.  Why wouldn't they do this?</P><P>1.  The system requirements alone are daunting.  Don't think so?  Go back and read the tons of posts on VI's tech support board stemming from the Luclin release (disaster) and look at the hardware people say that they have.  I myself am in my 30s and have enough disposable income that I can upgrade, within reason, to meet any hardware standard they may throw at me.  Not so for a large percentage of the current player base.  Many of the people playing the game now are high school and college age and don't necessarily have the means to make the jump to a GEForce 3, 700+ MHz processor, etc.   Also I imagine a lot of the younger players aren't going to easily talk mom and dad into footing the bill for an upgrade just to play a game.  I think VI also realizes that there are a lot of players who aren't going to make the grade with regard to hardware.  Think back to the money they had to fork out when they "accidently" forgot to mention Win95 and DX8 were incompatible.  They, in my opinion, didn't expect that to be a real problem.  A few upset players but no big deal and no big loss.  Well it turned out that there were a great many more people running Win95, and unable or unwilling to upgrade, than they thought. It was a public relations disaster that cost them a fair amount of money to salvage.</P><P>2.  While greater business mistakes have been made (think New Coke) it seems very unlikely that you put as much effort into EQ1 as VI has recently and at the same time plan to pull the plug in the very near future. This would be very costly to them because there would be no guarantee that the current player base will be willing to move.  In fact it could turn out to be the very opposite.  A move such as that could alienate (read piss off) the current players and send them looking elsewhere for online entertaiment.  I know in the past we have accepted the seemingly inane and inexplicable decisions they have made and all the nerfs that they have forced upon us.  Why did we do this?  Because we were attached to our characters.  They knew they could push us a pretty good ways based solely on the fact that we would be unwilling to give up something we have such an emotional attachment to.  If they pull the plug this won't be the case.  Everything we place such sentimental value on will be gone.  A geat many of us could finally do what emotional dependence on our other worldly avatars would never allow us to do in the past.  That would be to give a great big middle finger to VI and take our money elsewhere.</P><P>3. I think EQ2 may not turn out to be the great display of pyrotechnics that everyone thinks it will.  Sure it has great graphics. It addresses the issue of twinking.  Now stop and think for a second where we have heard these traits touted so loudly before. How long ago was it that we received the great announcement that a mighty knight was coming to slay the cumbersome old dragon known as EQ.  Anyone remember Dark Ages of Camelot.  It was going to bury EQ.  Its graphics were so awesome.  No more twinking and so on and so forth ad nauseum.  It was pretty and it did address some stated issues that players had but guess what.  Most of the people who left EQ came back after their free month was up.  Why?  Graphics alone don't get it.  Let's hope VI realizes that and isn't just chasing a technological willowisp that will land them in a pit of quicksand.  Also although many people will complain about twinking many people do it, most people do it in fact and want to continue to do it.  We all have our own definition of what is too much and what is going too far but I feel safe in saying we have all done it.  I know I have. My first character is now level 52.  I saved my ass off to get a full set of banded armor when that was some of the best stuff around.  I wore that crap until level 36 when I upgraded to the oh so uber Ivy Etched armor.  I have earned my stripes, I have paid my dues and I'll be damned if I want to go through all that crap each time I decide to make a new character.  The gear that I have now is by no means the state of the art uberest gear out there.  I had a hard enough time getting it that I don't want to see it decay.  I don't want to have to spend my valuable playing time running to an NPC to get it repaired and I want to be able to pass it down to any alt that I may wish to without having to worry that they can't use it at low levels or will tear it up trying.  The game mechanics that are being touted as so great will in my opinion not be satisfactory to a large number of people who are currently playing EQ and as such they will not leave to play EQ2, certainly not past any free trial period that VI may offer.  </P><P>4.  Finally, I don't think VI is stupid enough to turn 400,000+ people away who are standing in line with money in hand to play EQ.  EQ will live on until it is simply not financially practical to keep it going.  Who knows in 18 months I may get to eat these words but I think we can all rest easy that EQ as we know it will be around for a long time to come.  So buck up and keep striving for 60.</P><P> </font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Descartes</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> Not sure if some of what I"m about to say have been said (no way I'm reading such a long thread.)</P><P>It's common in text-based games (MUDs..weee) for there to be a complete player wipe every few years. So it's something I'm used to really. Now, if they don't offer transfers to EQ2 will I be mad? Well... I don't know, if I play EQ2 and it SOMEHOW makes playing all the way to lvl 200 actually fun, then no I won't care at all. I mean the main reason I think lots of people want transfers is just how truly BORING the lvl 50+ game in EQ is. When I first bought EQ it was still fairly new, and I was fairly new to graphical online games, it was "neato" all the way to lvl 50, even at lvl 50 I didn't feel like I had done everything. This is before Kunark even came out, because I knew there were other classes to play, and more things to get for my char. And plus it wasn't so horribly hard to level chars up (although certain hunting places got soooo damn crowded). Then of course level cap is raised to 60, and to get one char to 60 you have to focus so much attention on that one char you don't get time to enjoy a very wide diversity of classes. I mean unless you're a powergamer with no outside EQ life, no job, no family, there's not a very good chance of you getting say 5 or more lvl 60 chars. There's just not enough time in the day to do all that lvling and get good EQ for all the chars. </P><P>Now of course at first lvl 50-60 seemed great, mobs that were soo powerful and amazingly great items flying around. And then as you start to climb to 60 at first you feel pretty good fighting stuff that's at the upper tier of mobs. Then the horrid boring nature of sitting by yourself or even in a group and doing the same thing over and over again 1,000 times to move your xp. And the only real purpose of it all is to finally get to 60 so you can have "real" fun, then you find out lvl 60 doesn't exactly = fun, other than seeing 60 by your name and feeling a bit of an ego boost because of that.</P><P>Hmm so what Im' saying is if VI can find a way to make the high end game in EQ2 just as fun and ... with a sense of new discoveries as you level, as the lvl 1-50 game was then I won't have any problem at all with throwing all my chars away =0</P><P><BR> </font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Ravanta Suffer</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> Sadius:</P><P><a href="http://www.mudcentral.com" target="_blank">www.mudcentral.com</a></P><P>This is a website devoted to majormud, a text based mud that has been around since before the days of 286's.  I originally played this game using...........a 1200 baud modem.</P><P>*THIS GAME STILL EXISTS*</P><P>The original game I first started in, back in 92, maybe 93, IS STILL GOING.  Granted most don't play anymore (I finally stopped playing it 2 years ago) but there still making a respectable profit.</P><P>How can you say that they are going to pull the plug on eq1 just because eq2 comes out?  Playstation 1's still outsell most other video game systems, when the Playstation 2 has been out for over 18 months.</P><P>Sure, I think the server populations will die down a lot in EQ in the first few months of EQ2 releasing, but VI has a lot of servers, and if 1 falls to short on players to turn a profit, they will merge it with another low end server.</P><P>But who knows what could happen in the next 18 months until EQ2 is SCHEDULED to be released.  Even if its released on time, 18 months is an eternity for online games, and for all you know, any of the big5 multiplayer online games coming out *SOON* might dominate, and even turn away several EQ customers, and keep them away, unlike Daoc.  </P><P>Thats what I predict happening personally.  I think people want something fresh, something new, and I don't see the population getting that from EQ2, just because it is the same company after all.  People are fed up with a company saying such bogus statements such as 'risk vs. reward' when from day *ONE* they have not followed that on any level.  </P><P>But any way I look at it, EQ2 is going to be succesful, just because EQ1 has been successful.</P><P><img src="http://www.users.qwest.net/~morbid909/SIG4.jpg" border=0><BR> <br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=107355" target="_blank">Those who have turned away, shall be turned upon.</a>  <img src=icon_smile_evil.gif border=0 align=middle></font></td>
